Problem 1

Data from a gamma-ray satellite low Earth orbit. Counts the number of particles detected within a 100ms interval and orbits the earth in 90 minutes. Virtually all detections are from background cosmic rays, excepting gamma-ray bursts.

Zooming in and sampling data around this point reveals that this feature starts at exactly 315 degrees longitude and repeats for every 90 minute interval at this position. The orbital period is exactly 90 minutes so it is either this exact position or exact time.
% Counts are going high when the Earth longitude hits 315 deg! Or else
% there is a gamma ray burst every 90 minutes? Unlikely.
% Could be resetting instruments?
I will check briefly the solar phase to compare counts over a sample 90 minutes for two sets, out of phase by 180 degrees.
indices = find(mydata(:,3)==315);
% diff(mydata(indices,2)) each set the solar phase moves 24.0632 degrees
range1 = indices(6):indices(7);
range2 = indices(13):indices(14);

title("Overlay of 180 deg Solar Phase");
hold on;
plot(range1,mydata(range2,4));
hold off;
There does not appear to be a significant difference. We know the sun does not contribute significant gamma rays to earth unless there are solar flares.
A possible signal contamination would be the sudden sharp increase in counts every 90 minutes. This is highly unlikely to be a cosmic phenomena with this exact regularity, so it may be the instruments that are doing this. The background pdf() will have to accommodate this if it cannot be removed or corrected. I can build a different background for each part of the 90 minute interval.

3) The time dependence for the mean rate is found by averaging short intervals of the counts from each 90 minute period and fitting an exponential decay curve. This curve function allows us to conjure the mean rate parameter needed to create the background model at a time within the 90 minute interval. Some sample histograms with Poisson PDFs generated this way to demonstrate:
histogram(after315sample,"Normalization","pdf");
fun(1)
ans = 11.2256
mean(after315sample)
ans = 11.1837
testdist = makedist("Poisson","lambda",fun(1));
mydist = pdf(testdist,0:40);
hold on;
plot(0:40,mydist);
title("First Count From All 90 Minute Intervals");
hold off;
histogram(after315sample2,"Normalization","pdf");
title("10*60*60 Count From All 90 Minute Intervals");
fun(10*60*60)
ans = 6.0827
mean(after315sample2)
ans = 6.1921
testdist2 = makedist("Poisson","lambda",fun(10*60*60));
mydist2 = pdf(testdist2,0:40);
hold on;
plot(0:40,mydist2);
hold off;
It could be a little better, the mean is not perfect. Smaller binning intervals may produce better results but may make fitting more of a challenge.
4) A varying background results in different thresholds for discovery sensitivity. For backgrounds early in the 90 minute interval the mean rate is larger, meaning both the mean and the standard deviation (width, square root of mean) is larger. The '5 sigma' threshold for 100 millisecond gamma ray bursts is larger for earlier times than it is for later ones in this 90 minute orbital period.

There are only 10 time samples to examine and for each pixel there appears to be random fluctuations. The background does not appear to be time dependent at glance. To produce a background for a given time would require generating the background from a single image. To get the background I'd like to examine data from pixels where I'm fairly certain nothing resides. In the summed image I suspect these will be the darkest regions. I'll pick an arbitrary lower limit for the signal strength and see how many pixels are left available to use.

3) Signal hunt. The signals I am searching for (faint stars) will appear faintly on the summed image (CONDITION: that has had anomalous data removed?). The faintest stars will be the ones that skirt most closely to the threshold set by the background PDF, which let's say is '5 sigma'.
fivesigma = bgfullstd * 5
fivesigma = 2.7127
testhuntvalue = min(min(abs(sumimg - fivesigma)))+fivesigma % finds the signal value closest to 5 sigma
testhuntvalue = 2.7127
[huntrow,huntcol] = find(sumimg == testhuntvalue) % finds the location of the faintest signal
huntrow = 187
huntcol = 41
This can be done to find multiple faint stars.
